Mortality Time Series Data Cleaning (Philadelphia)

Christopher Cahill

The Data

The data comes from The CDC 122 Cities Mortality Reporting System (CMRS) which reports mortality numbers for 122 cities between 1962 and 2015. To examine the mortality and compare it with temperature and precipitation, climate data was downloaded from NOAA.

One initial issue that arose was that the mortality data was recorded at weekly intervals while the climate data was recorded at either daily or monthly values. As will be shown later, no valid model could be found from the mortality weekly data, so the decision was made to combine the mortality data into monthly values as opposed to combining the daily weather values to weekly.

Initial Import and Variable Selection

The full data set included 122 cities and only Philadelphia was to be examined, so first the mortality data was imported and limited to Philadelphia.

mortality<-read.csv('Full_Mortality.csv',header=TRUE)

mortality.phl<-mortality[mortality$City=='Philadelphia',]

Variables which were not needed were region, state, city (since we alrady know all values are from Philadelphia) and deaths broken down by age. While a breakdown by age would have been interesting to examine, the data did not break down pneumonia and flu deaths by age, and since these deaths were the main focus of the project, the age groups were excluded from further examination. Below shows a sample of the updated data set.

mortality.phl<-mortality.phl[,c(1,2,3,7,8)]

mortality.phl[1:5,]

Based on the below diagram, it was decided to only examine values from 1990 to 2012. While the full data set went to 2015, Philadelphia only recorded values to November, 2012.

The data was then reduced to include years starting in 1990.

mortality.phl<-mortality.phl[mortality.phl$Year>=1990,]

Problems Creating a Model

Evaluating large seasonal time series data sets is challenging when evaluating weekly data. In seasonal time series data, the model is fit to 6 different values for Autoregressive, Difference, Moving Average, and the same values for seasons. Using a loop function for the SARIMA(p,d,q,P,D,Q), values 0 through 4 were run for all 6 variables. That created 5^6 or 15,625 different possible models. Not one was statistically significant. This and other resources showing that monthly data is better at finding predictions and creating models. Now, the mortality data will be aggregated over weeks.

Finding Missing Values

Before the data can be aggregated and a valid model found, missing values from the data set must be found.

In order to look at missing values, the dates will need to be converted to a date format. A column of row numbers will also be added to make selection easier. Then, missing values will be found.

mortality.phl$Week.Ending.Date<-as.Date(mortality.phl$Week.Ending.Date,format='%m/%d/%Y')

mortality.phl$X<-1:nrow(mortality.phl)
#Pneumonia
mortality.phl[is.na(mortality.phl$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths),]

The above values show missing weeks for Pneumonia/Flu Deaths and All Deaths. To fill them in, the na.interpolation function in R will be used.

#Flu
missing.flu<-mortality.phl[is.na(mortality.phl$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths),6]
mortality.phl$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths<-na.interpolation(mortality.phl$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths)
mortality.phl[missing.flu,]

Aggregating the Data over Month

Now that the missing values have been interpolated, the rows can be aggregated over month. The year and month will be extracted from the date and death values will be added from rows with the same month and year.

#Philly

mortality.phl$MONTH<-substr(mortality.phl$Week.Ending.Date,1,7)

#Aggregate over week

Philly_monthly<-aggregate(Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths ~ MONTH, FUN=sum, data=mortality.phl, na.rm=FALSE)
Philly_monthly$All.Deaths<-aggregate(All.Deaths ~ MONTH, FUN=sum, data=mortality.phl, na.rm=FALSE)[,2]

Philly_monthly[1:10,]

The first ten rows show the new data with month and monthly mortality totals. Now a better model can be found.

The Improved Model

The auto.arima function provides values for the autogressive moving average model. Fitting these values into a model now produces much better results.

auto.arima(Philly_monthly$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths)

sarima.for(Philly_monthly$Pneumonia.and.Influenza.Deaths,12,1,1,1,1,1,0,12)
